HEADWORD: Lesion
<hw>Le"sion</hw> <pr>(l⟦emac⟧"zh⟦ucr⟧n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>l⟦eacute⟧sion</ets>, L. <ets>laesio</ets>, fr. <ets>laedere</ets>,
<ets>laesum</ets>, to hurt, injure.]</ety> <def>A hurt; an injury.</def>
Specifically: <sd>(a)</sd> <fld>(Civil Law)</fld> <def>Loss sustained
from failure to fulfill a bargain or contract.</def> <au>Burrill.</au>
<sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Any morbid change in the exercise of
functions or the texture of organs.</def>
<rj><au>Dunglison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

